<DOC><DOCNO> AP880406-0084 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1020EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Japan-COCOM     04-06 0221</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Japan-COCOM,0227</SECOND><HEAD>Police Search Trading Firms For Illegal Exports To China</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: A version on financial wire.</NOTE><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Police searched two trading firms after thegovernment accused the companies of exporting high-technologymeasurement equipment to China between 1985 and 1986 withoutobtaining permission.   The searches were conducted Tuesday at Kyokuto Shokai, homes ofthe firm's executives, and Shinsei Koeki, a Tokyo MetropolitanPolice official said.   The Ministry of International Trade and Industry charged Mondaythat both firms violated the nation's Foreign Exchange and ForeignTrade law by exporting high-technology equipment without obtainingpermission, the official said.   Seiji Murata, chief of MITI's export division, said KyokutoShokai exported to China five digital memory devices, anoscilloscope and one signal analyzer worth a total of $276,000between June 1985 and June 1986.   Shinsei Koeki is accused of shipping two sets of the digitalmemory devices worth $113,000 to China between August 1986 andNovember 1986.   The memory devices are used to gauge the intensity of anearthquake, but can have military applications, Murata said. Anoscilloscope is used to test microwave communications, while thesignal analyzer is used to pin down the source of noise. Both itemscan also be applied for military purposes, he added.   Officials of the two firms could not be reached Tuesday despiterepeated telephone calls.</TEXT></DOC>